Step 2 — Evaluation against that neutral-but-enthusiastic CD-listening stance: as a CD enthusiast who values listening experiences, important attributes are strong production quality, musical variety that rewards repeated listening, and historical or sonic significance that makes the CD worth spending time with. Thriller (widely known as Michael Jackson’s 1982 album) is famous for its high production values (Quincy Jones production), multiple internationally successful singles, tight rhythmic and dance-oriented arrangements, and broad stylistic variety across tracks. These qualities make it a compelling listening experience on CD: energetic dynamics, clear mixes, and memorable hooks that showcase what a well-produced CD can deliver. Peachtree Road (an Elton John album categorized here as Classic Rock / AOR) is a later, more subdued, album with an adult-contemporary/album-oriented rock approach; it can be rewarding for fans of Elton John and of mellow AOR productions, but it is less prominent in popular and historical impact and offers a more restrained, less varied listening palette compared with Thriller.
Step 3 — Why I choose Thriller and reject Peachtree Road: given that I have not specified a genre preference and that I "enjoy listening to CDs very much," Thriller is the better fit because it exemplifies the qualities that make CD listening engaging: exceptional, widely recognized production quality, dynamic and danceable arrangements that benefit from good playback equipment, and a tracklist with multiple standout songs that invite repeated listens and deeper appreciation of studio craft. Those finer attributes — punchy rhythm sections, layered arrangements, and a variety of tempos and moods across the disc — make Thriller an ideal pick for someone who values the listening experience itself. Peachtree Road, while artistically valid and suitable for listeners who prefer mature, laid-back singer-songwriter or AOR material, is comparatively monochromatic and less historically or sonically celebrated; it is more of a niche choice for devoted Elton John fans and therefore less aligned with the goal of selecting a CD that broadly showcases the pleasures of CD listening. For these reasons, I select Thriller and reject Peachtree Road.

