The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: Extracted preferences and dislikes (from my self‑introduction)
- Strong preference for intimate, piano‑forward singer‑songwriter records: warm, mic‑forward grand piano and a single conversational, midrange lead vocal dead‑center and kept uncrushed.
- Tactile analogue mastering with low compression that preserves transient attack, micro‑dynamics and generous headroom.
- Sparse, quiet percussion and tight sequencing so small gestures matter.
- Restrained, tasteful multi‑part harmonies that support rather than obscure the lead; low reverb so the vocal stays upfront and conversational.
- Also enjoy groove‑first live‑in‑the‑room recordings when present: elastic, tactile low end and punchy but well‑integrated bass and drums — but never at the expense of detail or transient snap.
- Dislikes that matter here: brick‑wall loudness, vocal‑burying reverb, shiny late‑’80s/AOR synth washes, dense harmonization that buries the lead, crunchy upper‑mid aggression, overpolished/maximalist mastering, and any processing that kills transient snap and headroom.
Why I selected candidate 2
- Candidate 2 directly matches the core items I listed: mic‑forward grand piano, dead‑center uncrushed lead vocal, tactile analogue mastering with low compression, preserved transient attack and generous headroom. Those are the primary sonic characteristics I prize for intimacy and vocal immediacy.
- It explicitly calls out sparse percussion and restrained, well‑separated harmonies, which align with my preference for quiet percussion and harmonies that support rather than obscure the lead.
- It also notes preserved micro‑dynamics and tight single‑disc sequencing and that it "avoids glossy AOR polish" — all concrete positives for me because they speak to low‑reverb upfront vocals, minimal overprocessing, and avoidance of the shiny late‑’80s/AOR aesthetics I dislike.
- In short, candidate 2 preserves the things I prioritized most: piano and lead vocal positioning and tone, analogue low‑compression mastering that keeps transients and headroom, and sparse tasteful arrangements.
Why I rejected candidate 1
- Candidate 1 emphasizes a mid‑focused remaster with "genuine tape warmth and mid‑forward guitars" and explicitly states this can "soften percussive attack and reduce upfront vocal immediacy." That directly conflicts with my demand for preserved transient attack and an uncrushed, conversational lead vocal dead‑center.
- The description calls out "punchy gated drums" and an arena sheen: gated/punchy drums and mid‑forward, guitar‑driven, tape‑warm arena treatments run counter to my preference for sparse, quiet percussion and tactile transient detail. Punchy gated drums tend to change the perceived space and attack in ways I dislike.
- While candidate 1 does list some positives (generous headroom, well‑separated harmonies, preserved solos), those don’t outweigh the core mismatches: the mid‑dominant, arena/tape sheen approach and softened percussive/vocal immediacy are antithetical to the intimate, piano‑forward, low‑compression sound I want.
